  "nursesNote": "Antipsychotics treat psychosis and schizophrenia. Typical agents (haloperidol, chlorpromazine) cause more extrapyramidal symptoms (EPS): acute dystonia (sudden muscle spasm needing benztropine or diphenhydramine right away), akathisia (inner restlessness), and pseudoparkinsonism (tremor, rigidity, shuffling gait). Tardive dyskinesia is a late effect of involuntary face and tongue movements that may be permanent, so the nurse watches for early signs. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome (high fever, severe rigidity, altered mental status, unstable vital signs) is a medical emergency: stop the drug and get help. Atypical agents (risperidone, olanzapine, quetiapine) cause more metabolic effects (weight gain, high glucose and lipids), so the nurse monitors weight and labs. Clozapine can cause agranulocytosis, requiring regular WBC/ANC monitoring. Antipsychotics take weeks to work fully and should not be stopped abruptly.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Assess for EPS, including acute dystonia and akathisia",
    "Watch for tardive dyskinesia and report early signs",
    "Treat neuroleptic malignant syndrome as an emergency: stop the drug",
    "Monitor weight, glucose, and lipids on atypicals",
    "Monitor WBC/ANC for patients on clozapine"
  ],
